description: From Middle English gerner, from Old French gernier, guernier, variant of grenier, from Latin grānārium (“granary”). Doublet of granary.

entries.meaning: A granary; a store of grain.
An accumulation, supply, store, or hoard of something.
examples: Master, I bring from many wanderings,The gathered garner of my years to thee;One precious fruit of many rain-blown springsAnd sun-shod summers, ripened over-sea.

verbs.description: garner (third-person singular simple present garners, present participle garnering, simple past and past participle garnered) (transitive)

entries.meaning: To reap grain, gather it up, and store it in a granary.
To gather, amass, hoard, as if harvesting grain.
examples: I walked enormous distances...garnering thoughts even from the heather.

entries.meaning: (often figurative) To earn; to get; to accumulate or acquire by some effort or due to some fact
examples: He garnered a reputation as a language expert.
Her new book garnered high praise from the critics.
His poor choices garnered him a steady stream of welfare checks.

entries.meaning: (rare) To gather or become gathered; to accumulate or become accumulated; to become stored.
examples: For this alone on Death I wreak / The wrath that garners in my heart;
